tux-im (0.1.0-10) resolute; urgency=medium

  * fix(lexicon): parse 4-column Rime dict lines so single-letter
    wubi codes ("level-1" 简码) load correctly.  Rime's
    wubi86.dict.yaml uses 4-column lines ``word<TAB>code<TAB>freq
    <TAB>stem``; the old parser used a greedy ``\S+`` regex that
    swallowed the entire 4-column line as a single word, then
    failed to match.  Net effect: every 4-column entry was dropped,
    including all 25 single-letter wubi codes (a->工, b->了,
    g->一, r->的, ...) — typing 'g' in wbpy mode produced no
    candidate at all.  Now try the 4-column pattern first, fall
    back to the 3-column pattern.  Adds 4 regression tests
    covering both formats, the single-letter wubi codes, and an
    end-to-end check against the real /usr/share/rime-data/
    wubi86.dict.yaml.  Word count goes from ~136,903 to ~136,928
    in the wubi trie.

 -- TUX IM contributors <tux-im@example.com>  Tue, 23 Jun 2026 12:30:00 +0000

tux-im (0.1.0-9) resolute; urgency=medium

  * fix(engine): normalise CapsLock-engaged letter keyvals in Latin
    mode.  When the user pressed CapsLock to enter English mode the
    physical LED stayed on, so every subsequent letter arrived at
    IBus as an upper-case keyval ('c' → 'C', 67).  With the engine
    in latin mode and just returning False, the upper-case keyval
    was forwarded to the focused app, producing capitalised
    characters even though no Shift was pressed.  Now the engine
    detects LOCK_MASK in the key state for alpha keyvals, commits
    the lower-case equivalent itself, and returns True so the
    forwarded event is replaced.  Digits, punctuation, and Chinese-
    mode input are unaffected.  Adds 7 regression tests in
    tests/test_capslock.py covering single letters, sequences,
    Shift+Caps, digits, punctuation, and chinese-mode pass-through.

 -- TUX IM contributors <tux-im@example.com>  Tue, 23 Jun 2026 12:05:00 +0000

tux-im (0.1.0-8) resolute; urgency=medium

  * fix(google_pinyin, wbpy): cap pinyin buffer to avoid
    libgooglepinyin crash.  19+ consecutive consonants in the
    pinyin buffer (e.g. a user holding down 'c') crashed
    MatrixSearch::extend_dmi with "Assertion `0 != handles[0]'
    failed" → SIGABRT → process core dump.  im_set_max_lens(30,
    50) was insufficient: the crash happens earlier for
    degenerate all-consonant inputs.  Now cap the pinyin engine
    buffer at 16 letters in both GooglePinyinMode.feed_key and
    WbpyMode.feed_key.  The visible buffer keeps growing (so
    the user can see what they typed) but the decoder is no
    longer called with the over-length string.  Adds a
    regression test that pins the cap constant in both files.

